===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{context|archaic|lang=en}} A seat of any kind.
#* Hampole
#*: upon the '''settle''' of his majesty
# A long [[bench]], often with a high back and arms, with storage space underneath for [[linen]].
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} A place made lower than the rest; a wide step or platform lower than some other part.
#* Bible, Ezekiel xliii. 14
#*: And from the bottom upon the ground, even to the lower '''settle''', shall be two cubits, and the breadth one cubit.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|settl}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To place in a fixed or permanent condition; to make firm, steady, or stable; to establish; to fix; especially, to establish in life; to fix in business, in a home etc.
#* And he '''settled''' his countenance steadfastly upon him,until he was ashamed. --2 Kings VIII. 11. (Rev. Ver.)
#* {{quote-book|year=1700|title=[[w:Metamorphoses‎|Metamorphoses]]|author=[[w:Ovid|Ovid]]|by=[[w:John Dryden|John Dryden]]|passage=The father thought the time drew on Of '''settling''' in the world his only son.}}
# {{context|transitive|obsolete|US|lang=en}} To establish in the pastoral office; to ordain or install as pastor or rector of a church, society, or parish.
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' a minister}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To cause to be no longer in a disturbed condition; to quieten; to still; to calm; to compose.
#* {{w|George Chapman}}
#*: God '''settled''' then the huge whale-bearing lake.
#* {{w|John Bunyan}}
#*: Hoping that sleep might '''settle''' his brains.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To clear or [[purify]] (a liquid) of [[dregs]] and impurities by causing them to sink
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' coffee, or the grounds of coffee}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To restore (ground, roads etc.) or bring to a smooth, dry, or passable condition
#: {{usex|lang=en|clear weather '''settles''' the roads}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To cause to sink; to lower
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' the contents of a barrel or bag by shaking it}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To determine, as something which is exposed to doubt or question; to free from uncertainty
#* {{w|Jonathan Swift}}
#*: It will '''settle''' the wavering, and confirm the doubtful.
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' the mind when agitated;&nbsp; to '''settle''' questions of law;&nbsp; to '''settle''' the succession to a throne;&nbsp; to '''settle''' an allowance}}
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To pacify (a discussion, quarrel).
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' a quarrel}}
# {{context|transitive|archaic|lang=en}} To adjust (accounts); to [[liquidate]]; to balance.
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' an account}}
# {{context|transitive|colloquial|lang=en}} To pay.
#*: to '''settle''' a bill
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[colonize]]; to move people to (a land or territory).
#: {{usex|lang=en|the French first '''settled''' Canada;&nbsp; the Puritans '''settled''' New England;&nbsp; Plymouth was settled in 1620.}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become fixed, permanent or stationary; to establish one's self or itself
#* {{w|Francis Bacon}}
#*: The wind came about and '''settled''' in the west.
#* {{w|John Arbuthnot}}
#*: Chyle{{...}}runs through all the intermediate colors until it '''settles''' in an intense red.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To fix one's residence; to establish a dwelling place or home.
#: {{usex|lang=en|the Saxons who '''settled''' in Britain}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become [[married]], or a [[householder]].
#* {{w|Matthew Prior}}
#*: As people marry now and '''settle'''.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To be established in a profession or in employment.
#: {{usex|lang=en|to '''settle''' in the practice of law}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become firm, dry, and hard, like the ground after the effects of rain or frost have disappeared.
#: {{usex|lang=en|the roads '''settled''' late in the spring.}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become clear after being unclear or vague
#* {{w|Joseph Addison}}
#*: A government, on such occasions, is always thick before it '''settles'''.
#: {{usex|lang=en|the weather '''settled''';&nbsp; wine '''settles''' by standing}}
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To sink to the bottom of a body of liquid, for example dregs of a liquid, or the sediment of a reservoir.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To sink gradually to a lower level; to subside, for example the foundation of a house, etc.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To become calm; to stop being agitated
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}}
#*: Till the fury of his highness '''settle''', Come not before him.
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To adjust differences or accounts; to come to an agreement.
#: {{usex|lang=en|He has '''settled''' with his creditors.}}
# {{context|intransitive|obsolete|lang=en}} To make a [[jointure]] for a wife.
#* {{w|Samuel Garth}}
#*: He sighs with most success that '''settles''' well.

